english:
  title: Third Memorial of the Same Petition
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The sun descends on mulberry and elm—I beg that this worn and weary frame be granted rest. Your Majesty's gracious words have fallen again and again like gentle rain, yet I find myself unable to receive such kindness. Forgive me for crying out once more.

    I reflect with utmost humility: I am a man of no particular talent fit for court service. Through presumption alone have I come to hold the reins of power, receiving only undeserved favor while accomplishing nothing of worth. Though I have striven to dispel darkness and repay your recognition, I am like one bearing a heavy load across a vast distance—nearly stumbling to ruin. When the court once entrusted me with military command, my spirit withered and I could not perform. When honors and stipends gathered upon this single frame, they overflowed their vessel without ceasing. I have reached the highest pinnacle of ministers and taken on the heaviest responsibilities of the court. My rewards have been immense, yet the censure I have endured is no less so. Had I retired when I should have, my shame would be less deep. Now that the time of my old age approaches, how can I remain unmoved? I have submitted my petitions, yet heaven does not grant them. Though Your Majesty's grace is as boundless as the sky and you have not hastened to cast me away, the mouths of ten thousand speak against me—how can I make them all understand? Should I be forced to remain by imperial command, there will surely be those who point and laugh at my face. I humbly beseech Your Majesty to hear my faint plea and grant me a life of leisure. Then might I wander peacefully through this blessed age, becoming an old man of ease in times of great peace, and in my twilight years complete whatever joy remains to me.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: '鼎台 (Ding Tai): The highest ministerial position; literally ''the tripod platform,'' alluding to the cauldron of state.'
  - key: ''
    value: This is a remonstrance memorial (表) in which a high official requests retirement, a common literary form in classical Chinese bureaucratic tradition.
